 9.55}], "images": [{"x0": 67.75, "y0": 4.85, "x1": 81.94, "y1": 6.84}, {"x0": 7.32, "y0": 4.93, "x1": 39.85, "y1": 7.12}, {"x0": 45.64, "y0": 0.9, "x1": 53.77, "y1": 6.96}, {"x0": 61.29, "y0": 2.1, "x1": 67.96, "y1": 6.81}, {"x0": 10.38, "y0": 15.71, "x1": 41.32, "y1": 16.96}, {"x0": 9.07, "y0": 13.67, "x1": 14.57, "y1": 17.55}, {"x0": 0.73, "y0": 0.43, "x1": 99.94, "y1": 12.8}, {"x0": -0.91, "y0": 0.5, "x1": 19.55, "y1": 12.73}, {"x0": 59.68, "y0": 24.14, "x1": 95.1, "y1": 44.92}, {"x0": 64.49, "y0": 46.74, "x1": 94.07, "y1": 63.43}, {"x0": 61.16, "y0": 64.59, "x1": 93.72, "y1": 90.01}], "full_text": "Lecture\nImaging of the CVS\nRadiology\n6\nAnatomical Foundation\nThe CVS is structurally composed of the heart and its associated vessels, including\narteries, veins, and lymphatics\nHeart Chambers and Septa\nThe heart is divided into four main chambers:\n-Right and left atria -Right and left ventricles.\n• Interatrial Septum: Separates the two atria.\n• Interventricular Septum: Separates the two\nventricles.\n• Atrio-ventricular Valve Groove: Defines the\nboundary between the atria and the ventricles.\nValvular Structure and Blood Flow\nValves ensure unidirectional blood flow through the\nsystem:\n• Atrio-ventricular (A-V) Valves:\n-Tricuspid valve (right) -Mitral/bicuspid valve (left).\n• Semilunar Valves:\nat the base of the aorta and pulmonary arteries, each\npossessing three cusps.\nRadiographic Borders and Surfaces\nWhen viewed via imaging, specific anatomical\nstructures form the cardiac silhouette:\n• Right Border: mainly of the right atrium\nwith smaller contributions from the SVC and IVC.\n• Left Border:\n-the left ventricle -the left atrial appendage\n-the aortic knuckle -the pulmonary artery.\n• Inferior and Anterior Surfaces: the right ventricle.\n• Posterior Surface (Base): Primarily the left atrium,\nwith parts of the left ventricle and inferior vena cava.\n80"}